component_text: removing classics from the shelves of libraries because they @MONTH1 offend certain people is completely unwarranted

they are not in agreement with their morals or beliefs

@PERSON2 @PERSON2 is a bestselling series with over a million copies that have been sold worldwide; however, it does not corrolate with many people's beliefs
Therefore those people boycott the series
I remember several years ago I attended a @PERSON2 @PERSON2 and the @CAPS1 @CAPS2 @CAPS3 party at the local library to celebrate the next book in the series being released
I was at the library there was a gigantic storm brewing
it was only a storm, but the people in town who did not like the @PERSON2 books blamed it on the party

I know many people do not like the @PERSON2 series

Even great novels like the @CAPS5 in the @CAPS6 should not be banned

what Katherine Paterson states is true
we do not agree with them or find them suitable, eventually there will not be any left to check out at the library
there could be a way to compromise
If the books with questionable content had a sticker on them telling the reader that, then it could benefit both sides
When I was young I would always want to be read to and when I continued to age I would always read
I was in middle school every day I would have a book with me to read
